  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>

        <div rend="parallel">
          <p xml:id="AN173.1-kilavi">talaimakaṉ piriviṉkaṇ vēṟupaṭṭa talaimakaḷait tōḻi <app><lem>vaṟpuṟuttiyatu</lem><rdg wit="#C2 #C3 #C9v">vaṟpuṟīiyatu</rdg></app>.</p>
          <p xml:lang="en">How the confidante consoled HER who had undergone changes during the separation from HIM.</p>
        </div>
        <div rend="parallel">
      <lg xml:id="AN173.1">
        <l>aṟantalai piriyā toḻukaluñ ciṟanta</l>
        <l>kēḷir <anchor n="1"/>kēṭupala vūṉṟalu<del>m</del> nāḷum</l>
        <l><supplied>va</supplied>runtā vuḷḷamō ṭiruntōrk killeṉac</l>
        <l>ceyviṉai purinta neñciṉar naṟunutaṉ</l>
        <l>maiyī rōti yarumpaṭa ruḻattal</l>
        <l>ciṉṉāṭ ṭāṅkal vēṇṭu meṉṟuni</l>
        <l>ṉaṉmā ṇelvaḷai tiruttiṉa rāyiṉ</l>
        <l>varuvar vāḻi tōḻi palapuri</l>
        <l>vār<supplied>ka</supplied>yiṟ ṟoḻukai nōṉcuvaṟ ko<supplied>ḷīi</supplied>p</l>
        <l>pakaṭutuṟai yēṟṟat tumaṇviḷi verīi</l>
        <l>yuḻaimā ṉampiṇai yiṉanīriṟan tōṭak</l>
        <l>kāṭukavi ṉaḻiya vuraiik kōṭai</l>
        <l>niṉṟutiṉa viḷinta vampaṇai neṭuvēy</l>
        <l>kaṇviṭat teṟikku maṇṇā muttaṅ</l>
        <l>kaḻaṅkuṟaḻ tōṉṟala paḻaṅkuḻit tāa</l>
        <l>miṉka<supplied>ḷi</supplied> naṟavi ṉiya<supplied>ṟēr</supplied> naṉṉa<supplied>ṉ</supplied></l>
        <l>viṇporu neṭuvaraik kavā<supplied>a</supplied>ṟ</l>
        <l>poṉpaṭu maruṅkiṉ malaiyiṟan tōrē.</l>
      </lg>
      <lg xml:lang="en">
        <l>He with a heart that desires work to be done, (4)</l>
        <l>thinking “Both conducting oneself without parting from virtue</l>
        <l>and to be depended upon in many adversities by exulted relatives</l>
        <l>is not for those who always sit [still], with minds that do not suffer”, (1-3)</l>
        <l>if he said “[you with] fragrant forehead [and] kajal[-black] moist hair,</l>
        <l>you must bear difficult affliction and endure for a few days!”</l>
        <l>[and] corrected [the position of] your good, glorious, bright bangles, (5-7)</l>
        <l>he will come [back], oh friend, (8a-c)</l>
        <l>– he who has gone to traverse the mountain with gold-yielding spots (18)</l>
        <l>on the slope of mountains [so] tall as to touch the sky, (17)</l>
        <l>of Naṉṉaṉ with an advancing chariot [and] sweet toddy, (16)</l>
        <l>where unpolished pearls that leap, when the nodes let [them] go, (14)</l>
        <l>of the long bamboo with pretty stalks that perished when constantly eaten (13)</l>
        <l>by the west wind, grating the wilderness so that [its] beauty is destroyed, (12)</l>
        <l>spread in old pits, [pearls] that appear like Molucca beans, (15)</l>
        <l>while the male deer with [its] herd of pretty does crosses the water [and] runs, (11)</l>
        <l>frightened by the call of the salt merchants at the bulls’ ascent from the ford, (10)</l>
        <l>making [their] sturdy necks pull the chariot with long ropes of many strands. (9)</l>
      </lg>
        </div>
    </body>
  </text>

